  "category": "Uncategorized",
  "description": "AI-Powered Smart Label Engine\n\nBuild an intelligent, prompt-driven labeling system that allows users to define natural-language rules for automatically classifying and tagging items (emails, tasks, action items, etc.) across the Krisp productivity hub.\n\nUsers define a label by providing a name and a plain-English matching prompt (e.g., \"Messages from FISD that contain Landon\"). The system uses an AI model to evaluate each item against the prompt and applies the label when the item matches the described criteria, eliminating the need for rigid keyword filters or manual tagging.\n\nRequirements:\n\nLabel Management\n- Provide a label creation UI where the user specifies a label name and a natural-language matching prompt\n- Support editing and deleting existing labels\n- Display all defined labels with their associated prompts in a settings or labels management view\n- Store labels in the Neon PostgreSQL database with fields: id, name, prompt, color (optional), created_at, updated_at\n\nAI Classification Pipeline\n- When an item is ingested or updated (email, task, action item, meeting, etc.), pass its relevant content (subject, body snippet, sender, etc.) along with all defined label prompts to the AI model (claude-sonnet-4)\n- Ask the model to evaluate which labels, if any, apply to the item based on the natural-language prompt\n- Apply all matching labels to the item and persist the associations in the database\n- Run classification on-demand (manual trigger) and automatically on new item ingestion\n\nLabel Application & Display\n- Display applied labels as color-coded chips or badges on emails, Kanban cards, action items, and meeting entries\n- Allow users to manually add or remove labels from any item, overriding AI suggestions\n- Support multiple labels per item\n\nFiltering & Discovery\n- Add label-based filtering to the email inbox, Kanban board, and action items views\n- Allow users to click a label chip to see all items sharing that label across all sources\n\nPerformance & Cost Controls\n- Batch classification requests where possible to minimize API calls\n- Cache classification results per item and invalidate only when the item content or label definitions change\n- Limit prompt evaluation to a configurable maximum number of labels per classification pass to control token usage\n\nEdge Cases to Consider\n- Items with no matching labels should remain untagged without error\n- Ambiguous or overly broad prompts should apply the label conservatively (require high model confidence)\n- Label deletion should cascade and remove all associations from previously labeled items\n- Very long email bodies should be truncated to a maximum token budget before classification",
  "title": "Implement AI-powered smart label engine for automatic classification",
